## WHAT IS GATIS AND WHY IT MATTERS

GATIS (General Active Transportation Infrastructure Specification) is a federally-backed, open-standard geospatial data framework from the Bureau of Transportation Statistics. Version 1.0 was ratified February 2026. It standardizes how cities/states record sidewalks, curb ramps, bike lanes, crossings, transit stops, and accessibility infrastructure. It is **public domain (CC0)**.

**Why this matters for Access Michigan:** The Transportation page currently shows bus routes and transit systems but has **zero sidewalk data, zero curb ramp data, zero bike infrastructure data, and zero pedestrian network data**. For Access Michigan's core users — seniors, people with disabilities, NEMT users — knowing whether they can safely *walk to* a bus stop or healthcare facility is more critical than knowing the bus route exists. GATIS fills this exact gap.

**GitHub repo:** `https://github.com/dotbts/BPA`
**Explorer:** `https://dotbts.github.io/BPA/`
**License:** CC0 Public Domain — no restrictions

